  <fr:p>Define the component <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta _{A}:\mathbf {hom}_{\mathcal {C}}{\mathopen {}\left (J,A\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> to be the composite <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[s;\alpha _{A}]]></fr:tex>; for the wild naturality structure, we fix <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f:\mathbf {hom}_{\mathcal {C}}{\mathopen {}\left (A,B\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> to define <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta _{f} : \beta _{A};f = 1_{J};\beta _{B}]]></fr:tex> as follows:</fr:p>

  <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {aligned}     \beta _{A};f & = {\mathopen {}\left (s;\alpha _{A}\right )\mathclose {}};f        \\                 & = s;{\mathopen {}\left (1_{A};\alpha _{B}\right )\mathclose {}}  \\                 & = s;\alpha _{B}                \\                 & = 1_{J}; {\mathopen {}\left (s;\alpha _{B}\right )\mathclose {}} \\                 & = 1_{J}; \beta _{B}   \end {aligned}   ]]></fr:tex>


  <fr:p>Next we identify <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta _{J}]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[1_{J}]]></fr:tex>. By incoherent naturality, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{J};s = \alpha _{I}]]></fr:tex>; thus by our splitting of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{I}]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _{J};s = r;s]]></fr:tex> and hence by postcomposing <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex> and canceling via <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\eta :s;r=1_{I}]]></fr:tex> we conclude that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _J = r]]></fr:tex>. Therefore <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta _J=s;\alpha _J=s;r=1_{J}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:tree
